Chronic, Progressive Confusion: Dementia

I seem to have lost all my intellectual faculties, but I feel very well, thank you.




Ralph Waldo Emerson (probably had Alzheimers Disease)

Dementia

  • Definition: A syndrome characterized by a change or decline in cognitive function sufficient to cause impairment in social and occupational performance.



(Dr.Mark Sager, UW Alzheimers Institute, 2003)

Costs of Dementias

  • Prevalence*
    • 5.3 million in U.S., 16 million in 2050
    • 20 million in world; 50-60 million
    • 100,000/year deaths
    • 10 30 % of nursing home patients
  • Economic
    • $100 billion annually in U.S.
    • Families; $200,000 per illness


*Dr.Sanjay Asthana, 2009, Institute on Aging

Types of Dementia

  • Alzheimers Disease
  • Multi-Infarct or vascular dementia
  • Dementia with Lewy Bodies
  • Frontotemporal dementia (rare)



- Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI)

Alzheimers Disease (AD)

  • Most common form of dementia (50 60%)
  • 1906*, Dr.Alzheimer found beta-amyloid plaques and neurofibrillary tangles during a brain autopsy
    • Augusta D. Im losing my brain
  • Mild, moderate, and severe forms (stages)
  • Slow or rapid progression
  • 8 10 years average life span (up to 20)

Prevalence of Alzheimers Disease at different ages

Causes of AD

  • ?? Unknown whether brain changes are a cause or effect of AD
  • AD may be a disease that begins very early in life but becomes symptomatic or causes functional problems much later in life
    • Nun study
  • Risk factors: age*, APOE4 allele in late onset,
    • Heart disease, DM, head trauma, Downs syndrome, APP670/671; APP717, APSE4, chromosome 14)

Brain with AD

  • Plaques (amyloid protein) and tangles (tau protein), especially in frontal cortex
  • Neuronal loss in hippocampus and neocortex = marked reduction in brain weight
  • Changes in neurotransmitters (serotonin, acetylcholine)?
  • Excess Beta amyloid (protein) deposits in brain**



**probably causative

Multi-Infarct or Vascular Dementia

  • A series of small strokes or cerebral infarcts
  • Symptomatic when sufficient brain cells destroyed
  • Can be periods of improvement, then new symptoms with recurrent infarcts
  • Underlying cause can be prevented (e.g., HTN)

Dementia with Lewy Bodies (DLB)

  • 15 25% of dementias
  • Lewy bodies found on autopsy
  • Symptoms
    • dementia
    • visual hallucinations
    • EPS
    • Differentiate from parkinsons
    • IMPORTANT = sensitivity to neuroleptic medication (severe)

Mild cognitive Impairment (MCI)

  • Ongoing memory problems progressive forgetfulness
  • More than normal age complaints
  • No confusion, attention, language problems
  • May be early form of AD or lead to AD

Should there be screening for AD?

  • Current guidelines say No
  • If cognitive impairment suspected use
    • Direct observation
    • Patient report
    • Reports of family, friends, caretakers


      (USPSTF screening guidelines, 2003)

7 warning signs of AD for patients and families

  • Asking the same questions over and over
  • Repeating the same story, word for word, over and over
  • Forgetting how to perform well-known tasks (cooking, tying shoes)
  • Forgetting how to pay bills, balance checkbook
  • Getting lost in familiar surrounding; misplacing objects
  • Neglecting hygiene
  • Letting someone else take over making decisions

Behavioral symptoms and course of dementia (AD)

  • Mild (early)
    • memory problems, difficulty with complex IADLs, depression, withdrawal, denial
  • Moderate
    • disoriented to time, place; assistance with complex ADLs
  • Severe - (late)
    • Personality changes, agitation, psychotic symptoms, incontinence, eventual loss of all verbal or psychomotor ability

More AD symptoms

  • Catastrophic reaction
  • Sundowning
  • Decreased impulse control
  • Poor judgement
  • Concrete thinking
  • Apraxia (eating milk with fork)
  • Sleep disturbance
  • Seizures

More AD symptoms (cont)

  • Aphasia, swearing
  • Perceptual difficulties
  • Repetitive behaviors
  • Wandering
  • Mood swings
  • Paranoia
  • Personality change
  • Sexually inappropriate
  • Delusions/hallucinations

Emotional responses to AD

  • Attempts to conceal deficits, manage (early)
  • Withdrawal, depression (early, mid)
  • May be full or partial awareness of symptoms
  • Denial (early) versus anosognosia (late)
  • Grief, anger, guilt, confusion, attempts to cope

Distinguishing Dementia from Depression & Delirium

Treatments

  • Ineffective/controversial*
    • Antioxidants/vitamin E
    • Gingko
    • NSAIDS
    • Estrogen/serms still being studied
    • Statins still being studied

      *Dr.Sanjay Asthana, 2009, Insititute on Aging Colloquium

FDA approved medications for AD

  • Acetylchoninesterase inhibitors mild to moderate AD
  • Galantamine (Reminyl)
  • rivastigmine (Exelon)
  • donepezil (Aricept)
  • NMDA antagonist - severe AD
  • Memantine (Namenda)
  • Improve symptoms in early AD; No effect on progression or pathology

Behavioral problems in dementia

  • Depression (40%)
    • accelerated course of AD if depression untreated
  • Psychosis (33%)
  • Agitation/aggression (80%) (can be due to psychosis)
    • Wandering
    • Verbal abuse/inappropriate verbalizations
    • Inappropriate or aggressive behavior

Triggers

  • Most problems occur while providing personal assistance
  • Often a reaction to the perception of threat
    • Loss of personal space
    • Frustration with declining abilities
    • Discomfort (cold, pain)
    • Loss of control/choice
    • Unfamiliarity with routine

Communication Strategies

  • Reality orientation (early)
    • nonconfrontive!
  • Validation therapy (late)
  • Distract, redirect if delusional
  • Teach these skills to families!

General principles

  • Focus on the person, not the task
  • Take a minute to assess the person & situation
  • Break tasks into steps, allowing person to do what he/she is able
  • Respond to the emotional communication (dont argue logically)
    • Try to find the emotional message
    • attempts to remain engaged in life
  • Use the patients agenda
  • Redirect the person with a positive approach
  • If things dont go well, leave and try again later

Environmental Modifications

  • Space
  • Low stimuli
  • Routine and structure
  • Bright light
  • White noise
  • Music

Exercise training

(JAMA, 2003; U. Washington school of nursing)

  • Home-based exercise training + caregiver behavioral management training
  • MMSE 16.8 (moderate-severe)
  • Effects on:
    • Mobility (Balance, strength, flexibility, muscle mass, falls)
    • Depression

Medication management

  • Antidepressants
    • SSRIs, SRIs
  • Antipsychotics Becoming controversial
    • 23% of elderly with dementia treated for psychosis
    • hallucinations (visual & auditory)
    • delusions
    • agitation
    • aggression
    • paranoia, jealousy

Antipsychotics in the elderly

  • Conventional (haldol, chlorpromazine)
    • Anticholinergic effects
    • Postural hypotension
    • Parkinsonism
    • Sedation
    • Akathisia
    • Tardive dyskinesia!!! A major increased risk with age
    • Falls/fractures

Atypical antipsychotics

(risperidone, olanzapine, quetiapine)



In 2008, studies showed no effect on overall behavior but increased risks

Other med management

  • Anti-anxiety drugs
    • Caution - May worsen symptoms
    • Lorazepam, alprazolam, buspirone
  • Sleep
    • Trazodone
    • AVOID BENADRYL, VALIUM

  • Effects on physical and psychological health of caregivers

  • 1 in 4 family members provide care for someone with Alzheimers
  • Caregiver age
    • Average = 57
    • 35% over 65
    • 10% over 75
